---
import CaseStudy from "../../layouts/CaseStudy.astro";
import Compare from "../../components/Compare.astro";
import Figure from "../../components/Figure.astro";
---

<CaseStudy
  eyebrow="Template preview · Dummy content"
  title="Sample Case Study"
  outcome="This page exists to prove the case-study template renders end to end — every real project drops into this same structure."
  role="Design & front-end"
  timeline="Template · Day 2"
  tools={["Astro", "Figma", "React"]}
  liveUrl="https://cansinbayir.com"
  figmaUrl="https://figma.com"
  repoUrl="https://github.com/cansinba/portfolio"
>
  <h2>Problem &amp; constraints</h2>
  <p>
    Every case study on this site follows one fixed structure so a hiring manager
    can scan any project the same way. This is placeholder prose sized to show the
    reading measure — the line length should sit between 60 and 75 characters, which
    is the comfortable range for sustained reading. If a line runs much wider than
    this, the eye loses its place returning to the next line.
  </p>
  <p>
    The constraint that shapes everything here: a reader gives a portfolio maybe
    three minutes. The template has to make the outcome legible immediately, then
    reward anyone who keeps reading with the reasoning behind it.
  </p>

  <h2>Process</h2>
  <p>
    The body of a case study walks through how the work was made. It carries at least
    one image or artifact roughly every 150 words so the page never becomes a wall of
    text. Here is a standard figure with a caption:
  </p>

  <Figure
    src="/assets/sample/design.svg"
    alt="Placeholder design mockup"
    caption="A standard figure sits at the prose width with a muted caption underneath."
  />

  <h3>The pipeline</h3>
  <p>
    Every project shows one direction of the Figma↔code workflow. This is the
    signature artifact — two panels, labelled, so the match between the design and the
    shipped implementation is something you can see rather than a claim you have to
    trust.
  </p>

  <Compare
    figmaSrc="/assets/sample/design.svg"
    codeSrc="/assets/sample/build.svg"
    figmaAlt="Placeholder Figma design"
    codeAlt="Placeholder shipped code"
    direction="figma-to-code"
    caption="Figma design (left) and the shipped React implementation (right) — same layout, same spacing."
  />

  <h2>Key decisions</h2>
  <p>Three decisions, each paired with the alternative that was rejected and why.</p>

  <div class="decision">
    <h3>1 — One fixed template over per-project layouts</h3>
    <p>
      A single structure makes the whole portfolio scannable and keeps publishing fast:
      new project, fill the slots, ship.
    </p>
    <p class="rejected">
      <strong>Rejected:</strong> bespoke layouts per project — more expressive, but slow
      to build and inconsistent to read across seven case studies.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="decision">
    <h3>2 — Show the pipeline, don't describe it</h3>
    <p>
      The side-by-side comparison component turns the core claim into visible evidence
      on every project page.
    </p>
    <p class="rejected">
      <strong>Rejected:</strong> a paragraph explaining the workflow — easy to skip, easy
      to doubt.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="decision">
    <h3>3 — System fonts and inline SVG for speed</h3>
    <p>
      Keeping the page dependency-light protects the Lighthouse budget and loads instantly
      on a throttled connection.
    </p>
    <p class="rejected">
      <strong>Rejected:</strong> a heavy web-font pairing up front — better typography, but a
      cost to pay only once the design is settled.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>Outcome &amp; what's next</h2>
  <p>
    The template renders at <code>/work/sample</code>, stays readable on mobile, and gives
    every future project a prepared slot to drop into. Next: replace this dummy content with
    the first real project (Basalt UI) and its captured pipeline artifact.
  </p>
</CaseStudy>
